  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "JK",
    "text": "This is me, Joe Kempler, taken in Krakow in park. I would put myself possibly at about three years old. So this would be 1931. So this is the only picture I have of this particular time. [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] This is my sister on the left, Judy Kempler. At that point, she was called Judy Laub, L-A-U-B. And this is me, in-- Joe Kempler, in 1937 when I was nine years old. The place is [? Krynitza, ?] which is a Polish resort town, and I visited her at that time. [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] This handsome young man is Joe Kempler again, after the war. It's-- I'm exactly 19 at this point. This is a photo for an ID card for the Landsberg DP camp and is the first photo I have after the war. [PAUSES FOR 5 SECONDS] This is a picture of my sister and her husband, Andrew Billys, B-I-L-L-Y-S, taken in Denver, Colorado. They were married in 1950. This, I think, is their wedding photo. He committed suicide in 1963. So they were married for about 13 years. And he, as I said before, the reason really is unknown, but he was a survivor as well. [PAUSES FOR 4 SECONDS] This is my first wife, Marion Dreifuss. We were married in February of 1953. And she died of Hodgkin's disease three years later. [PAUSES FOR 7 SECONDS] In-- in November 1963, I married again to Virginia Vrbanich. And this is the-- my wedding photo. And is a-- a wonderful looking young couple. We are still married at this time. [PAUSES FOR 5 SECONDS] This is a snapshot of the wedding of my daughter, Susan. So the-- Susan is the one, of course, in the wedding gown. Her husband is to her right.",
